            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Daniel Park\u2019s story is etched in the silver halide of San Francisco\u2019s fog. The only son of Korean immigrants who ran a small, bustling grocery store in the Inner Richmond, Daniel grew up stocking shelves and translating for his parents, but his real world was framed through the viewfinder of his father\u2019s old Minolta camera. His parents, pragmatic and hardworking, saw his photography as a hobby, pushing him toward a more stable career. He enrolled at City College of San Francisco to appease them, but while he excelled in the darkroom, his interest in general education waned.\n\nThe turning point came during a massive city protest. Armed with his camera, he felt an electric connection to the unfolding history, capturing raw emotion with an instinct that couldn't be taught. He sold a powerful shot to a local paper and, tasting the thrill of the profession, never returned to class. For over a decade, Daniel hustled as a freelance photojournalist, documenting the city's shifting soul\u2014from the dot-com boom\u2019s extravagance to its subsequent busts. The work was vital but financially precarious.\n\nIn his late 30s, seeking stability after a marriage frayed by financial stress and unpredictable hours ended amicably, Daniel took a full-time position. He now works as a photojournalist for a large foundation in SoMa, documenting their community outreach and grant-funded projects. The work is meaningful and provides a steady paycheck, but he sometimes misses the raw energy of the streets.\n\nNow 48, Daniel lives a quiet, ordered life in a rent-controlled apartment in the same Richmond District where he grew up. His daily 5.1-mile commute on the Muni 38R is a ritual of observation, his eyes scanning faces and street corners for untold stories. He maintains a small circle of old friends and a cordial relationship with his ex-wife. His dream is to one day have a solo gallery show of his personal work: stark, black-and-white images of San Francisco\u2019s overlooked moments. He still carries his camera everywhere, a quiet observer forever in love with the city that raised him, always searching for the perfect light."
        },
